reative interventions can help develop social connectivity and resilience for older people is vital in developing a holistic cross-sector approach towards ageing well. Academics with a wide range of expertise critically reflect on how the built environment, community living, cultural participation, lifelong learning, and artist-led interventions encourage older people to thrive and overcome both challenging life events and the everyday changes associated with ageing. The book uses a range of approaches, including participatory research methods, to bring the voices of older people themselves to the foreground. It looks at how taking part in creative interventions develops different types of social relationships and fosters resilience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aBailey, Cathy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBattersby, Lupin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernard, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuys, Laurie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanham, Sarah L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavenport, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavenport, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDonoghue, Geraldine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspinoza, Adriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFacer, Keri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFang, Mei Lan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilroy, Rose, eco